theorem putnam_1972_a6
(f : ℝ → ℝ)
(n : ℤ)
(hn : n ≥ 0)
(hfintegrable: IntegrableOn f (Icc 0 1))
(hfint : ∀ i ∈ Icc 0 (n-1), ∫ x in Icc 0 1, x^i*(f x) = 0)
(hfintlast : ∫ x in Icc 0 1, x^n*(f x) = 1)
: ∃ S, S ⊆ Icc (0 : ℝ) 1 ∧ MeasurableSet S ∧ volume S > 0 ∧ ∀ x ∈ S, |f x| ≥ 2^n * (n + 1) := by
  have hn' : (n : ℝ) ≥ 0 := by exact_mod_cast hn
  have h1 := hfint 0 (by
    -- Show that 0 is in the interval [0, n - 1]
    norm_num
    <;> rcases n with (_ | _) <;> simp_all [Int.le_iff_lt_or_eq]
    <;> linarith)
  have h2 := hfint (n - 1) (by
    -- Show that n - 1 is in the interval [0, n - 1]
    norm_num
    <;> rcases n with (_ | _) <;> simp_all [Int.le_iff_lt_or_eq]
    <;> linarith)
  -- Use the fact that f is integrable and the given integrals to derive a contradiction
  use Icc 0 1
  constructor
  -- The set Icc 0 1 is a subset of itself
  exact Icc_subset_Icc (by norm_num) (by norm_num)
  constructor
  -- Icc 0 1 is measurable
  exact isCompact_Icc.measurableSet
  constructor
  -- The volume of Icc 0 1 is positive
  simp [volume_Icc, Real.volume_Icc, hn']
  <;> norm_num
  <;> positivity
  -- For all x in Icc 0 1, |f x| ≥ 2^n * (n + 1)
  intro x hx
  have h3 := hfint 0 (by
    -- Show that 0 is in the interval [0, n - 1]
    norm_num
    <;> rcases n with (_ | _) <;> simp_all [Int.le_iff_lt_or_eq]
    <;> linarith)
  have h4 := hfint (n - 1) (by
    -- Show that n - 1 is in the interval [0, n - 1]
    norm_num
    <;> rcases n with (_ | _) <;> simp_all [Int.le_iff_lt_or_eq]
    <;> linarith)
  -- Use the given conditions to derive the inequality
  norm_num [hx] at h1 h2 h3 h4 ⊢
  <;> simp_all [abs_of_nonneg, abs_of_nonpos, sub_nonneg, sub_nonpos]
  <;> nlinarith [pow_nonneg (by positivity : (0 : ℝ) ≤ 2) n]
